The patient’s symptoms of vomiting, not passing stool, and presence of an abdominal mass suggest intussusception, which occurs when one segment of the intestine invaginates into the lumen of an adjacent segment. Meckel’s diverticulum is an outpouching of the intestine, Duodenal atresia is a blockage of the small intestine, and pyloric stenosis is a narrowing of the lower end of the stomach that leads into the small intestine. None of these conditions present with the same symptoms as intussusception.
